<br>
I like to protect and help people. At one time I considered joining the police force, but in the end I changed my mind. The reason I did is because there would be people I would meet who would be so vile, sinister, and wrong that I would probably lose self control. A word for this is an abomination. One example are child molesters or rapists. If I met one on the job and saw what they did I'd probably beat them to death out of rage and anger. There are things in this world that call out to me for action, judgement and an immediate end.<br>
<br>
That said, if God is all good and just, viewing any imperfection, however small to still <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> be imperfection</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, then He would <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> HAVE</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to act upon it. Because we are all sinners and are imperfect (since we're talking about the Biblical God here), if God showed Himself to everyone I doubt He'd get off a &quot;Hi guys!&quot; before everyone ceased to exist. This is why God always appears in the form of a cloud, a burning bush, etc. or uses angels (his messengers) to communicate. Heck, even Moses in his prime was only allowed to see the back of God's form, or else he would be destroyed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;But if God is all-knowing, then why haven't we ceased to exist, since he knows that we are imperfect?&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> That's a very good question that I'm sure a lot of people are thinking right now. My own thoughts on this is that God, being all-merciful, allows us this time under the excuse that we are ignorant of his being and thus should not be judged until we have had the last possible moment to &quot;work it out&quot;. When does that time run out? Judgement day. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
In the Biblical sense humanity is flawed and corrupt, imperfect along with everything else of this world in the eyes of God. Originally atonement sacrifices were instigated <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> by</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> man between man and God over every little sin, in which God put His anger and rage upon that little lamb instead of that sinful person. When the lamb was slaughtered, that sin was separated from the man. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (&lt;---See where I'm going with this? Hehe. )</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Nowadays the lambs have it easy, only having to worry about dinner time. Instead of lambs I as a Christian use Jesus. No I don't nail Him to a cross every time I make a mistake, I simply accepted the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> final</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> atonement sacrifice instigated <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> by</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> God. I believe that God placed all the accumulated sin of the world of all ages upon Jesus including my own, judged it upon Calvary, and released me from the price of my sin (eternal death, that is, separation from God.) All I had to do was accept God's offer of the perfect sacrifice and allow Him to separate me from my sins. In doing so, it changes the very nature of your being, no longer seen as corrupt, flawed, or imperfect, but rather your intrinsic being is seen as Christ is to God.<br>
<br>
Tying this in with the whole heaven issue, I believe you will only see people who accept Christ or made atonement sacrifices in the old testament in the presence of God. He simply cannot allow imperfection in His presence, otherwise He would be forced to act upon it. Through Christ you will be seen as flawless and perfect in the eyes of God. There are no faction quests with God either. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  You can't donate money to the poor, attend church all your life, cure cancer, etc. and expect God to like you better than He did before. He already loves you to death...literally. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  All you have to do, all you CAN do is simply accept Christ as payment for your sins. That's it. <br>
<br>
When you accept Christ and are separated from your sins, that doesn't mean you <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> stop</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> sinning. It just means that all the things you have done, are doing, and will do are forgiven, nullified in the eyes of God--they don't exist. That forgiveness is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> permanent</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> as well. No matter what you do God will still see you as a perfect being, even if you are a child molester or rapist. That doesn't mean people will or should treat you any differently, however. They probably won't.<br>
<br>
Here's a funny little fact.. The word &quot;Sin&quot; is from Archery, a term used when you miss the Bullseye. You could hit the target a centimeter from the bullseye or miss the target by ten feet, yet it's all the same. They're all sin. <br>
<br>
I don't see God as a fluffy lovey parent who lets his kids do whatever they want. I see Him as a loving parent who, in his love, disciplines and teaches his children how to act and live the best life possible. I don't see Him as wishy-washy on issues either. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Those are my thoughts. <p><br><center><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=76175"><IMG SRC="http://www.PageProducer.com/users/HiroBrinstar/sahasrahla.gif"></A><br>Sahasrahla, Wizard<br>Agahnim, Enchanter<br>Vazaelle</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/usiggymk5.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SiggyMk5</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1418<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/18/02 9:18:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=226>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.in-your-ear.net/rejkid.gif  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Somebody should start a religion thread</span><hr size=1> I've always thought the Christian obsession with original sin was ridiculous.  Having read the Bible a gazillion times, I just don't see it as being such a big deal as Christian dogma makes it out to be...<br>
<br>
Again I'll note here that I'm not Christian, but if I were, my interpretation would be something like this--God gave man free will.  When humanity was young in the the Garden of Eden He took care of us, but His plan was never to keep us there, we were always meant to grow beyond that relationship and he placed the adversary in the Garden to force us to think and make decisions and eventually come to know Good and Evil and mature.  But of course, once we were mature it was time for God to let us go into the world and learn by ourselves and progressively over time He has become less and less directly involved as humanity has grown up.  There was no original sin, there was simply the divine plan which required humanity to leave the Garden just as a child must eventually leave the home of their parent.  God had to behave in an angry and wrathful way so that we would learn to seperate ourselves and take care of ourselves.<br>
<br>
By the time Jesus comes around, humanity is spread across the globe in hundreds of thousands of different groups.  We had grown up, and even begun to grow old.  JC arrived to impart God's most important wisdom, that of love and tolerance then because we had not been prepared to hear it before.  We were too young and rash.  And when He left, he had to do it in a way that was permanent, so that now, armed with all God's wisdom and generations' experience we could be completely our own.  At the same time, though, He wanted to let us know, again now that we were ready, about the good life that was prepared for us upon our departure from the mortal frame.  These two things were his ultimate gift to us.  Of course, believing in God was important, but not so much as taking His wisdom to heart.  When God created man we were his children and he had to teach and guide us, but now that we've grown up, He wishes as was always His divine plan, to have us as companions.<br>
<br>
After JC, God moved on.  This is not to say He doesn't still check in on us once in a while and occasionally offer us a guiding hand, but for the most part He has let us grow as we please, for better or worse.<br>
<br>
In my interpretation, modern Christianity should not be about fearing God or sin and redemption, but rather about passing on the wisdom that has been given us so that we do not forget the things which are important, or from whence we came.<br>
<br>
Now obviously, my interpretation is quite different, at least superficially, from most mainstream ones.  I mean no disrespect to the many great sages and scholars who over the millenia have devoted their lives to pondering the questions of faith and come up with different ideas.  I just don't agree with many of them.<br>
<br>
And again, I'm not a Christian, though I have read a multitude of English translations of the Bible, as well as some more 'original' Greek and Hebrew versions as it's my business to do so.  I don't claim my interpretation is any more correct than any other.  The very nature of the storytelling of the Bible makes it impossible to make any claim with absolute certainty.  These are just my thoughts on the message of the text and, like all interpreters, I weighed some messages in the text over others and in a few cases all but completely ignored some because I felt them to be contrary to the thrust of the text and with no particular reason.  I don't claim my interpretation is any more correct than any other.<br>
<br>
Anyhow, that's my 2 shekels.<br>
<br>
